entry.title: SyncToSigninMigration: Fix flakiness in EG tests
entry.content:
The tests sometimes failed because there was already data on the

FakeServer at the beginning of the test. This was (apparently) because

the previous test had cleared the FakeServer, but not actually ensured

that those changes get flushed out to disk (which can happen because

the EG framework doesn't always cleanly shut down the app under test).

This CL fixes this by adding explicit "flush to disk" calls after

clearing data.

entry.title: [IdleTimeout] Part 1 of EG Tests for IdleTimeout and IdleTimeoutActions
entry.content:
This is the first part of the tests for IdleTimeout policies egtests.

This mainly tests the cases for showing the dialog and the snackbar.

More tests will be written to test specific actions.



The cases tested and their expectations are as follows:



- `Continue using Chrome` button clicked: no actions run, the snackbar is now shown and the dialog is not dismissed

- The dialog counts down 30 seconds without user interaction: dialog is dismissed, actions run and the snackbar is shown.

- The dialog is shown then the app is backgrounded: on re-foreground, the actions run and the dialog is not shown. The snackbar shows after actions run.

- Multiple windows: The dialog shows in one of the windows

- Multiple windows and the window showing the dialog is closed: the dialog should transfer to the other window still opened.



The CL also fixes and improves a few bugs that affects some tests and improve consistency of the variables that the service has access to.

entry.title: [mullet] Update metrics to handle new M3 use cases.
entry.content:
Why?



Turns out M3 for passwords is also going to have full form filling

(This was not initially true). This means the regular popup

for passwords will be updated to also have children suggestion,

not only when triggering from the context menu.



Therefore we will want to measure whether users will use full filling

or field by field filling also for passwords.

This metric is measured by the FillingMethodUsed,

which before was making no differentiation between filling products.

Since the assumption was that only addresses would have non

field-by-field filling.



To go ahead and for completion I am also starting to log

FillingMethodUsed for unclassified fields

(which can only be field by field filling) and log field-by-field

filling for unclassified fields as well. With this, it will be easier

to just add new buckets in the future.



Metrics:



*MethodUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*MethodUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.Address.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

*FieldTypeUsed.CreditCard.TriggeringFieldMatchesFillingProduct



One caveat about these metrics is that TriggeringFieldDoesNotMatchFillingProduct

bucket can only happen on field by field filling

(the other filling methods require field classification).



Note: The feature is not rolled out, therefore we do not have to

worry about losing metrics.



DEMO: https://screencast.googleplex.com/cast/NTYwMzAxNzU0MDc2MzY0OHw3NGUzMDA3Ny1mOQ



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAMS=Moved to a more more fine grained granularity to

account for new use cases.

entry.title: Remove PDMCleaner::alternative_state_name_map_updater_for_testing()
entry.content:
The PDMCleaner doesn't own the alternative state name map updater, but

the PDM does. So instead, tests that need to access it should go

directly via the PDM.



This CL:

- Removes PDMCleaner::alternative_state_name_map_updater_for_testing()

and adds PDM::get_alternative_state_name_map_updater_for_testing()

instead.

- Updates all calls of the above function.

- Removes PDM::personal_data_manager_cleaner_for_testing(), which got

unused as a result.

- Removes some #ifdef UNIT_TEST from personal_data_manager.h. Chromium

has a presubmit script [1] that ensures that for-testing functions are

only called in tests. And the macro is an ODR violation [2].



[1] https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/HEAD/styleguide/c++/c++.md#tests-and-test_only-code

[2] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/3798587/comment/f50c0b2b_467f01d4/

entry.title: [Policy] Mark policy fetch during device enrollment as critical
entry.content:
A bit of history:

2016: The "critical" flag is sent for some policy fetch requests:

https://codereview.chromium.org/2458653003



2019: The "critical" flag is sent for all policy fetch requests,

probably by accident, because marking everything as critical defeats the

purpose.

https://crrev.com/c/1614059



2023: The "critical" flag is sent for no policy fetch requests,

maybe by accident, but it does not really make a difference whether

all fetches are marked or none.

https://crrev.com/c/5041520



This CL recreates the original intent: Mark policy fetches during device

enrollment as critical.

entry.title: [ios] Fix hangs during shutdown if many sync-ing tabs
entry.content:
The main practical difference is that some observer functions are

invoked a bit later:

1. WebStateObserver::WebStateDestroyed()

2. WebStatePolicyDecider::ResetWebState()



With ~85 overrides for the first, and although many of them appear to

be trivial (e.g. just removes the observer), it is hard to be sure

about undesired side effects.



That said, one of them, IOSChromeLocalSessionEventRouter::Observer,

is a clear beneficiary: the fact that WebStateList gets trimmed at

once, and before WebStateDestroyed() is invoked, avoids quadratic

runtime behavior in sync code, which iterates the entire WebStateList

every time WebStateDestroyed() is invoked.

Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^chrome/" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""



echo "IncludeBlocks: Regroup" >> ".clang-format"

echo "IncludeIsMainRegex: \"(_(android|apple|chromeos|freebsd|fuchsia|fuzzer|ios|linux|mac|nacl|openbsd|posix|stubs?|win))?(_(unit|browser|perf)?tests?)?$\"" >> ".clang-format"

git cl format

git restore ".clang-format"



git cl format

```

entry.title: [waffle]Add an accessibility label to the chevron
entry.content:
Adding a tabindex to the cr-radio-group element will make the screen reader read its content. We don't want that to happen so we remove the tabindex which will make it non-accessible by Tab but in the normal flow, the screen reader would only read the number of items in the group.



The cr-radio-button element is not read by the screen reader by default. We usually directly go to the button inside it (the circle).



Instead of doing that, we add a label to the whole cr-radio-button element which contains the button, chevron, search engine name and icon so that we know what the whole element is. We added the label as the name of the search engine.



Now, when going into the cr-radio-button, we read the search engine name one more time and this is redundant.

We add an aria-hidden="true" to the search engine name to stop that from happening.



The screen reader will read the aria-label of the chevron and add collapsed or expanded based on its state.



What remains is the button (circle) which is the main part of the cr-radio-button element. From https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/webui/resources/cr_elements/cr_radio_button/cr_radio_button.html;l=4?q=cr_radio_button%20lang:html we can see that the button circle is described by the content that's slotted inside it. The circle will ignore the search engine name because of the aria-hidden attribute and then will proceed to read the chevron label and then state that we are on a radio button.



Screen recording: http://b/317481808#comment6



Fixed: b:317481808, b:317481638

entry.title: Create URLLoaderThrottles in the background thread
entry.content:
Currently if the BackgroundResourceFetch feature is enabled, when Chrome

fetches a subresource, URLLoaderThrottles are created in the main

thread at LoaderFactoryForFrame::CreateURLLoader(). And they are passed

to the background thread after DetachFromCurrentSequence() is called in

BackgroundURLLoader::Context::Start().



This is not good for performance. For example, safe_browsing::

RendererURLLoaderThrottle needs to clone a new mojom::SafeBrowsing mojo

handle. This triggers a method call MojoSafeBrowsingImpl::Clone() in

the browser process main thread which is very busy. We should not call

this method for every subresource requests.



To solve this problem, this CL does followings:

1. Make BackgroundResourceFetchAssets keeps a cloned

URLLoaderThrottleProvider and LocalFrameToken. And make

BackgroundURLLoader create URLLoaderThrottles using the them on the

background thread.

2. Don't use BackgroundURLLoader in prefetch only (NoStatePrefetch)

documents. It is because NoStatePrefetchHelper::MaybeCreateThrottle()

method doesn't work on the background thread. This CL introduces

IsMainThread() check in NoStatePrefetchHelper::MaybeCreateThrottle(),

and IsPrefetchOnly() check in LoaderFactoryForFrame:

CreateURLLoader().

entry.title: Make IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle work on non-main thread
entry.content:
Currently IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle is not created by

URLLoaderThrottleProvider when CreateThrottles() is called on non-main

thread. So IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle don't work for subresource requests

from workers. This is not a big issue since login and logout requests

are rarely sent by workers.



But it will be a problen when we will call CreateThrottles() of a cloned

URLLoaderThrottleProvider on the background thread for normal

subresource requests from frames for BackgroundResourceFetch feature

(crrev.com/c/5113665).





So this CL does followings:

1. Keep the main thread task runner in providers

(URLLoaderThrottleProviderImpl and

ShellContentRendererUrlLoaderThrottleProvider).

2. Make CreateThrottles() method of the providers create

IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle even when it is called on non-main thread.

3. In the callback of MaybeCreateIdentityUrlLoaderThrottle, use the

main thread task runner to call blink::SetIdpSigninStatus() in the

main thread when the callback is called on non-main thread.
